     The 'trace' command will change the current  mode  to  trace
     mode.   In  the trace mode there are commands that allow you
     to set trace  points  at  subprogram  calls  and  subprogram
     exits,  the  start  and  end  of  the elaboration of package
     bodies and exceptions.
     The commands used in the trace mode to set trace  points  on
     events  and  exceptions all need the name of a subprogram or
     package.  The notation used to  enter  these  names  is  the
     selected component notation.


     EXAMPLE :

            PPROCEDURE test IS
                    PROCEDURE black IS
                            PACKAGE box IS
                                    -- types and objects of box;
                            END box;
                            PACKAGE BODY box IS
                            BEGIN
                                    -- statements of box;
                            END box;
                    BEGIN
                            -- statements of black;
                    END black;
            BEGIN
                    -- statements of test;
            END test;


     The name of package box in selected  component  notation  is
     'test.black.box'  .   The  name  of procedure black would be
     'test.black' while that of procedure test is simply 'test'.

     In this simple example we can easily name all subprogram and
     packages  but  in  real  life  the  DAS  programs are not so
     simple.  With most DAS programs it would thus  take  a  long
     time to name all subprograms and packages.

     To prevent this long and boring task the effect of naming  a
     particular  subprogram  or  package is to implicitly include
     all the subprograms and packages declared in the declarative
     part of the explicitly named subprogram or package.

     So instead of naming all subprograms  and  packages  in  the










